'''''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''''' (also known as '''''Disney Infinity 2.0 Edition'''''<ref name=MetacriticReview/><ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity|url=https://infinity.disney.com/order|publisher=[[Disney]]|accessdate=12 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609181931/https://infinity.disney.com/order|archivedate=9 June 2015}}</ref>) is an [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[Nonlinear gameplay#Sandbox mode|sandbox]] [[toys-to-life]]<ref name="latimes.com"/> [[video game]] developed by [[Avalanche Software]] and published by [[Disney Interactive Studios]]. The game features additional work by Studio Gobo and [[Ninja Theory]]. It is the sequel and successor of the 2013 video game ''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]'' and was announced on April 8, 2014. The game was released on September 23, 2014 in North America, September 19, 2014 in the United Kingdom, September 18, 2014 in Australia and the rest of Europe for [[iOS]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Wii U]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Xbox 360]] and [[Xbox One]],{{ref|1|1}} and for [[PlayStation Vita]] on May 9, 2015.

Featuring original story material by [[Brian Michael Bendis]], ''Marvel Super Heroes'' includes three plots and includes characters from both [[Marvel Entertainment|Marvel]] and [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] properties. The main campaign is divided into three stories. The first storyline follows the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]] as they prevent the [[Norse mythology|Norse God]] [[Loki (comics)|Loki]] from rebuilding the [[Casket of Ancient Winters]]. The second storyline centers on [[Spider-Man]] and features him and his team tasked with the objective to stop [[Green Goblin]]'s [[Symbiote (comics)|symbiote]] invasion. The third and final storyline concentrates around the [[Guardians of the Galaxy (2008 team)|Guardians of the Galaxy]], in a plot heavily inspired by the ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' film, where the Guardians must protect [[Knowhere]] from [[Ronan the Accuser]].

''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' expands ''Disney Infinity''{{'}}s array of tools to use in the Toybox mode, an open world sandbox. Additionally, the ability to personalize individual characters has been added, using a Skill Tree. ''Marvel Super Heroes'' adds on the previous game's community sharing options, including the sharing of personal creations.

It was also the first Marvel-licensed game to be published by Disney Interactive Studios, due to [[Sega]]'s contract with Marvel expiring after the release of ''[[Captain America: Super Soldier]]'' in 2011, and [[Activision]]'s contract expiring after the release of ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2 (2014 video game)|The Amazing Spider-Man 2]]'', released a few months prior to the release of ''Marvel Super Heroes''. A sequel, ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]'', was released on August 28, 2015 in Europe and August 29, 2015 in North America.

==Plot==
The game follows multiple plots, with each Playset having its own.

===Avengers Playset===
The Avengers Playset centers on [[Loki (comics)|Loki]] and [[MODOK]] attempting to rebuild the [[Casket of Ancient Winters]], with the aid of the [[Giants (Marvel Comics)|Frost Giants]],<ref name=Marvel/> in order to freeze [[New York City]].<ref name=Xbox>{{cite web|url=http://news.xbox.com/2014/06/games-disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-e3|title=We Can Be Heroes in Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes|author=Xbox Wire Staff|publisher=Xbox Wire|accessdate=July 13, 2014|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref>

===Spider-Man Playset===
The Spider-Man Playset, which is heavily inspired by ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man (TV series)|Ultimate Spider-Man]]'',<ref name=Webs/> centers on [[Green Goblin]] and [[Mysterio]] cloning the [[Venom (Marvel Comics character)|Venom symbiote]] and launching a symbiote invasion.

===Guardians of the Galaxy Playset===
The Guardians of the Galaxy Playset, which is heavily inspired by the ''[[Guardians of the Galaxy (film)|Guardians of the Galaxy]]'' film in terms of design, centers on the Guardians stealing an [[Infinity Gems|Infinity Stone]]<ref name=SDCC/> from [[Ronan the Accuser]]. Ronan follows the Guardians to the planet [[Knowhere]]. With the help of Cosmo the Spacedog and [[Collector (comics)|The Collector]] the Guardians must protect Knowhere from Ronan and the Sakaaran fleet.<ref name=Guardians>{{cite web|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2014/07/23/guardians-of-the-galaxy-coming-to-disney-infinity|title=DISNEY INFINITY: MARVEL SUPER HEROES -- TOY BOX / 23 JUL 2014 GUARDIANS OF THE GALAXY COMING TO DISNEY INFINITY|last=Krupa|first=Daniel|publisher=[[IGN]]|date=July 23, 2014|accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref> The Guardians of the Galaxy eventually make way onto Ronan's ship, the Dark Aster, to defeat him once and for all.<ref name=SDCC/>

==Gameplay==
[[File:Captain America and the Skill Tree, from Disney Infinity Marvel Super Heroes.jpg|thumb|left|The Skill Tree upgrade system]]
''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' features similar gameplay to ''Disney Infinity''. Each character can equip a "Pack" or a "Tool." Packs are items that are worn and can be equipped on a character's back, occasionally shown as some sort of [[backpack]]. Tools are items, such as rifles, that can be equipped in a character's hand. Some aspects of the game, however, have been changed. In addition to ground movement, certain characters will be able to fly and hover.<ref name=Polygon>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/4/30/5668684/disney-infinity-2-marvel-super-heroes|last=McWhertor|first=Michael|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Edition with Marvel Super Heroes coming this fall|date=April 30, 2014 <!-- at 1:19pm --> |accessdate=May 1, 2014|publisher=Polygon}}</ref> The size of Toybox worlds and Playset have been increased, notably due to the inclusion of flying.<ref name=Polygon/> Certain characters can climb walls, including the Hulk.<ref name=IGN/> The level cap of playable characters has been expanded from Level 15 to Level 20.<ref name=Polygon/> Characters can be "leveled up" by collecting sparks.<ref name=Capsule/> A "Skill Tree" has been incorporated into the game and can be used to upgrade a character's abilities.<ref name=CTV/><ref name=Forbes/><ref name=NUK/> The figures from the first game will also receive additional abilities through the Skill Tree.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/gaming/2014/06/24/disney-infinity-marvel/11309519/|title=Marvel heroes join the battle in 'Disney Infinity'|last=Molina|first=Brett|date=June 24, 2014|accessdate=July 12, 2014|publisher=[[USA Today]]}}</ref> The choices made in the Skill Tree are semi-permanent, as players have the options to reset the Skill Tree choices by resetting their character to Level 0.<ref name=Capsule/> Some characters can jump long distances, including Hulk.<ref name=Xbox/> Each character plays differently from another,<ref name=SDCC/> with characters being roughly divided into two categories, Ranged and Melee.<ref name=Stuff>{{cite web|last1=Robertson|first1=Andy|title=Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes preview|url=http://www.stuff.tv/my/playstation-4/disney-infinity-20-marvel-super-heroes/review|website=stuff.tv|publisher=Stuff|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> Ranged characters fight from far distances, while Melee characters fight using close combat. Signature moves can be unlocked as the player progresses.<ref name=Nerdist/> For example, Drax primarily utilizes short-ranged melee attacks to defeat enemies, while Star-Lord can use ranged pistols.<ref name=SDCC>{{cite web|title=SDCC 2014: DISNEY INFINITY: MARVEL SUPER HEROES|url=http://marvel.com/news/video_games/2014/7/26/22966/sdcc_2014_disney_infinity_marvel_super_heroes|website=marvel.com|publisher=[[Marvel Comics|Marvel]]|accessdate=26 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729063731/http://marvel.com/news/video_games/2014/7/26/22966/sdcc_2014_disney_infinity_marvel_super_heroes|archivedate=July 29, 2014|deadurl=yes}}</ref> As characters are leveled up, new abilities will be unlocked.<ref name=Prima/> Iron Man's ground slam and Hulk's Thunderclap<ref name=Prima/> abilities can be unlocked once players have enough Skill Points. Characters' upgrades differ. Iron Man can upgrade his blasting capabilities, while Thor and Hulk can upgrade their strength, using the new Special Skills and Combat system.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Workman|first1=Robert|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes Announced|url=http://www.primagames.com/games/disney-infinity/news/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-announced|website=primagames.com|publisher=Prima Games|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> All upgrades, skills and progress applied to the character will be saved to the figurine.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Robertson|first1=Andy|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 plays the Marvel card|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2014-05/01/disney-infinity-2/viewgallery/yt9l7eiZGEF8s|website=wired.co.uk|publisher=Wired|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> The freeform unlock system in ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' replaces the roulette-based unlock system from ''Disney Infinity''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cowan|first1=Danny|title=Beyond Infinity: Disney Infinity 2.0's mechanical evolution|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/06/11/beyond-infinity-disney-infinity-2-0s-mechanical-evolution/|website=joystiq.com|publisher=Joystiq|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref> If a player is defeated in-game, they must wait a certain time frame until they can use the character they were using again.<ref name=Forbes3/> A map scanner has been implemented to allow players can get around worlds more easily.<ref name=Forbes3/> Mission givers are also present in the game.<ref name=Forbes3/> In order to web-sling players do not need to attach their webs to surroundings near by.<ref name=Webs>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=53498|title=HANDS-ON: BENDIS TAKES A KEY ROLE IN "DISNEY INFINITY 2.0: MARVEL SUPER HEROES"|date=June 17, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2014|last=Rougeau|first=Mike|publisher=Comic Book Resources}}</ref>

''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' is split up into two game modes: Playset and Toybox (referred in ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' as Toybox 2.0.)<ref name=Yahoo/> In Playset mode, players can play [[open world]] multiple story modes based specifically on a certain franchise. Each Playset spans from 6–10 hours in length.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Loveridge|first1=Sam|title=Disney Infinity 2.0|url=http://www.trustedreviews.com/disney-infinity-2-0_Games_review|website=trustedreviews.com|publisher=Trusted Reviews|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> These Playsets can be accessed by placing the Playset piece (also known as a crystal shard piece)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gaudiosi|first1=John|title=Disney and Marvel take interactivity to 'Infinity 2.0' and beyond|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-05-07/entertainment/sns-201405071130--tms--invideogctnzs-a20140507-20140507_1_disney-infinity-disney-interactive-phil-coulson|website=articles.chicagotribune.com|publisher=Chicago Tribune|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> on the Disney Infinity Base, a [[near field communication]]-enabled<ref name=NFC>{{cite web|last1=Dyer|first1=Karl|title=Disney Infinity NFC figure video game begins shipping|url=http://www.nfcworld.com/2013/08/19/325552/disney-infinity-nfc-figure-video-game-begins-shipping/|website=nfcworld.com|publisher=NFC World|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> hexagonal platform that has two round spots to place figures (and use in them in the game) and one hexagonal spot to place the Playset piece or Power Discs. Only figures, usable in the game through near field communication technology,<ref name=NFC/> that are from a Playset's corresponding franchise can be used in that Playset. Certain characters, including Nova, Iron Man, Rocket Raccoon and Hulk<ref name=Capsule/><ref name=Yahoo/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://infinity.disney.com/en-ca/characters/iron-man|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes (2.0 Edition) - Iron Man (from Marvel's The Avengers)|accessdate=July 12, 2014|publisher=infinity.disney.com (Disney Infinity official website)}}</ref> are playable in more than one Playset, by collecting tokens (called "Cross Over Tokens")<ref name=Capsule>{{cite web|last1=Day|first1=Andrew|title=Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes Impressions|url=http://www.capsulecomputers.com.au/2014/08/disney-infinity-2-0-marvel-super-heroes-impressions/|website=capsulecomputers.com.ai|publisher=Capsule Computers|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> scattered throughout levels.<ref name=Wonder>{{cite web|last1=Sunu|first1=Steve|title=SDCC: THE WONDER OF "DISNEY INFINITY 2.0"|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=54514|website=comicbookresources.com|publisher=Comic Book Resources|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> Once players have collected ten Cross Over Tokens for one character,<ref name=Capsule/> that character can be used in another Playset and will unlock exclusive storylines. The Avengers Playset and the Spider-Man Playset take place in "Marvel Manhattan," a version of [[Manhattan]] that is 4x larger than ''[[The Incredibles]]'' Playset featured in the first ''Disney Infinity'' title.<ref name=Marvel/><ref name=Polygon/><ref name=IGN>{{cite web|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2014/04/30/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-announced|title=Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes Announced|last=Dyer|first=Mitch|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 1, 2014|publisher=IGN}}</ref><ref name=CTV/>''The Incredibles'' Playset was the largest environment in ''Disney Infinity''.<ref name=Arc>{{cite web|last1=Dickey|first1=Josh|title='Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes' Lets You Fly, Thunder, Smash — and Build|url=http://mashable.com/2014/04/30/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes/|website=mashable.com|publisher=Mashable|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> While in Playset mode, players will be able to uncover secret missions and new goods that can be used in the Toybox.<ref name=Prima/>  Bendis will pen the stories and dialogue of all future Marvel Playsets.<ref name=Marvel/> Local multiplayer can be accessed through [[Split screen (computer graphics)|split screen]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Mike|title=Disney Infinity Marvel Super Heroes: When One Corporation Owning Everything Rocks|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-when-one-corporation-owning-everything-rocks|website=usgamer.net|publisher=US Gamer|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

[[File:The Toy Box Game Maker, from Disney Infinity Marvel Super Heroes.jpg|thumb|right|The Toy Box Game Maker tool, which can be used to restrict access to perform certain actions]]
The latter game mode, Toybox mode is a [[Nonlinear gameplay#Sandbox mode|sandbox]] mode that allows players to create their own games and worlds, using items unlocked in Playset mode.<ref name=HandsV/> Certain characters, including [[Tinker Bell]], can not be played inside Playset mode and only in Toybox mode.<ref name=NI>{{cite web|last1=Seedhouse|first1=Alex|title=Tinker Bell & Nick Fury receive Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes sneak peek|url=http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2014/07/29/tinker-bell-nick-fury-receive-disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-sneak-peek/|website=nintendo-insider.com|publisher=Nintendo Insider|accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref> Toybox mode supports local and online multiplayer.<ref name=Forbes3/> In Toybox mode, players are given a "Magic Wand,"<ref name=HandsV>{{cite web|last1=Houlihan|first1=Paul|title=Hands on with Disney Infinity 2.0 Marvel Super Heroes|url=http://www.vooks.net/hands-on-with-disney-infinity-2-0-marvel-super-heroes/|website=vooks.net|publisher=Vooks|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> which can be used to place items around the [[Nonlinear gameplay#Sandbox mode|sandbox]], customize items and access the Toy Shop<ref name=HandsV/> (a virtual shop where players can purchase new items for use in the Toybox.) The Magic Wand can also be used to set commands on objects, using "Game Logic." Creativi-Toys, objects in the Toybox, that can be set to use Game Logic return in the game, with 75 new additions.<ref name=Lapl/> For example, a player can set a party cannon to shoot confetti if they connect the cannon to a button. Players can also restrict access to certain packs and tools in the Toybox, including the Magic Wand.<ref name=Lapl/> The Toy Shop replaces the Toy Spinner from the first game.<ref name=Capsule/> Items that can be used in Toybox mode can be unlocked through Playset mode.<ref name=HandsV/> In an attempt to make Toybox building easier, the game will feature improved and enhanced Toybox editor tools (including in-game "brushes", that will automatically create scenery for players, including cities, dungeons and race tracks).<ref name=Polygon/><ref name=NUK>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialnintendomagazine.co.uk/57859/blog/disney-infinity-20-why-im-excited-twice-over/|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 - Why I'm Excited Twice Over|date=May 16, 2014|first=Colette|last=Barr|publisher=Official Nintendo Magazine|accessdate=May 24, 2014}}</ref> Templates, pre-built mini-games when placed into a world or "Auto Creators"<ref name=Nerdist/> are also present in the game.<ref name=Template>{{cite web|last1=Stuart|first1=Keith|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes – toying with older fans|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/jul/29/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes|website=theguardian.com|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> Templates range from Cliff-side [[beat 'em up]] Battle Arenas<ref name=Template/> (similar to [[Super Smash Bros.]]) to obstacle courses. Players can then tweak and change Templates to their liking.<ref name=Nerdist/> In order to add some Templates into the Toybox, players must decide the length, width and height of a box, that will house and generate the desired structure.<ref name=Capsule/> A Challenge Maker has also been implemented into the game, allowing players to create structured games.<ref name=Lapl>{{cite web|title=Disney Announces Toy Box Features of Disney Infinity (2.0 Edition)|url=http://www.laughingplace.com/w/news/2014/08/14/disney-announces-toy-box-features-of-disney-infinity-2-0-edition/|website=laughingplace.com|publisher=Laughing Place|accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> Result screens were also added for competitive play Toyboxes.<ref name=Lapl/> A new feature introduced in ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' is the Text Creator, which allows players to write their own text bubbles in the Toybox.<ref name=Lapl/> All text, however, must be filter and moderated through a safe chat server.<ref name=Lapl/> The game also introduces the Toy Box Game Maker, a tool that can restrict access to certain actions, including the use of the Magic Wand.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hare|first1=Chris|title=Disney reveal enhanced Toy Box mode in Disney Infinity 2.0|url=http://connecteddigitalworld.com/2014/08/14/disney-reveal-enhanced-toy-box-mode-in-disney-infinity-2-0/|website=connceteddigitalworld.com|publisher=Connected Digital World|accessdate=24 August 2014}}</ref> An undo button has also been implemented into the game.<ref name=News2/> Objects from the first game can be unlocked in ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' by placing a ''Disney Infinity'' Playset piece on the ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' base.<ref name=Com>{{cite web|url=https://infinity.disney.com/en-ca/compatibility|title=Disney Infinity Compatibility|publisher=Disney Infinity official website|author=Disney Infinity|accessdate=July 24, 2014}}</ref> will also feature automated builders, that can be dropped into the Toybox and generate worlds for players.<ref name=Polygon/> Automated builders include Eve from ''[[WALL-E]]'' and Sultan from ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]''.<ref name=Wonder/> In the Toybox mode players will also be able to create interior areas, a feature absent from the first game.<ref name=Joystiq/> Interior areas (styled in-game as INteriors)<ref name=Capsule/> can also be themed to certain characters.<ref name=QB>{{cite web|last1=Ching|first1=Albert|title=BENDIS & QUESADA WELCOME MARVEL SUPER HEROES TO "DISNEY INFINITY 2.0"|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=52517|website=comicbookresources.com|publisher=Comic Book Resources|accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref> More than twenty rooms can be added inside an INteriors.<ref name=Capsule/> Multiple INteriors can be connected through doorways inside buildings.<ref name=Capsule/>

In ''Disney Infinity'' each figure had their own "Adventure," a playable level that was made specifically for the character. Toybox Adventures will not be returning in ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''.<ref name=Forbes3>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andyrobertson/2014/06/17/disney-infinity-2-0-venom-merida-maleficent/|title='Disney Infinity 2.0' Adds Perma-Death For Marvel Heroes|date=June 17, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2014|last=Robertson|first=Andy|publisher=[[Forbes]]}}</ref> An introductory Toybox is pre-loaded into the game, and is filled with Game Play Hosts, who can assign missions and answer questions a player may have.<ref name=Lapl/> Rewards are given to players once Game Play Host mission are completed.<ref name=Lapl/> Players can share their Toybox creations with friends by uploading them onto the internet.<ref name=Prima>{{cite web|last1=Workman|first1=Robert|title=Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes First Look|url=http://www.primagames.com/games/disney-infinity/feature/disney-infinity-20-marvel-super-heroes-first-look|website=primagames.com|publisher=Prima Games|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=14Aug/> To help incorporate the new sharing features, a Newsfeed screen was added to the main menu.<ref name=Lapl/> Players can upload up to 300 Toyboxes to a private cloud and can save up to 100,000 Toyboxes.<ref name=Lapl/> Players can "like" favorite published Toyboxes and find other Toyboxes, that have found positive reception from other players.<ref name=Lapl/> In order to make searching through the shared Toyboxes easier, players can set categories and filters that apply to the Toybox that they want to play in.<ref name=Lapl/>

The game introduces Toybox Games, discs which allows players to create games based on genres such as tower defense and dungeon crawling.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bonthuys|first1=Darryn|title=Avengers Assemble! Disney Infinity 2.0 Marvel Super Heroes announced|url=http://www.lazygamer.net/general-news/avengers-assemble-disney-infinity-2-0-marvel-super-heroes-announced/|website=lazygamer.net|publisher=Lazygamer|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> Each Toybox Game is around 3–4 hours in length.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Diener|first1=Matthew|title=Avengers assemble - Disney Infinity Marvel Superheroes coming to iPad and PC tablets this fall|url=http://www.pocketgamer.co.uk/r/iPad/Disney+Infinity+Marvel+Superheroes/news.asp?c=59275|website=pocketgamer.co.uk|publisher=Pocket Gamer|accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref> The tower defense Toybox Game is set in [[Asgard (comics)|Asgard]] and called ''Attack on Asgard''.<ref name=Yahoo/> In ''Attack on Asgard'', Loki will command Frost Giants to invade [[Odin (comics)|Odin's]] Palace.<ref name=Yahoo>{{cite web|title=Marvel’s Guardians of the Galaxy Play Set Coming to Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes (2.0 Edition)|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/marvel-guardians-galaxy-play-set-130000200.html|website=finance.yahoo.com|publisher=[[Yahoo]]|accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref>

Power Discs, physical discs placed on the Infinity Base to unlock skies, textures and in-game toys, will return from the first game.<ref name=Forbes/> There are two types of Power Discs, Circular and Hexagonal. Circular Power Discs give in-game boosts to playable characters and Hexagonal Power Discs unlock skies, textures and in-game toys (including vehicles.)<ref name=QB/> The game will also feature two-wheeled vehicles, like motorcycles in addition to four-wheeled vehicles.<ref name=CTV>{{cite news|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/entertainment/disney-introducing-marvel-superheroes-to-infinity-game-1.1800888|title=Disney introducing Marvel superheroes to 'Infinity' game|agency=Associated Press|date=May 1, 2014 <!-- 7:59AM EDT --> |accessdate=May 3, 2014|publisher=[[CTV Television Network|CTV News]]}}</ref> Eighty-two Power Discs are to be released.<ref name=PowerDiscs/> Some Power Discs will feature "Team-Ups". Team-Ups will make other characters pop up in-game to fight alongside the player.<ref name=Forbes/> Certain Power Discs will also unlock new costumes for characters,<ref name=Forbes/> including [[Gamora]]'s "space armor."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Molina|first1=Brett|title='Disney Infinity' recruits Guardians of the Galaxy|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/gaming/2014/07/23/infinity-guardians-galaxy/13039799/|website=usatoday.com|publisher=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> Additionally, some Hexagonal Power Discs can launch "Area of Effect" attacks.<ref name=Nerdist>{{cite web|last1=Forté|first1=Malik|title=MORE JUICY DETAILS ON DISNEY INFINITY: MARVEL SUPER HEROES|url=http://www.nerdist.com/2014/05/everything-you-need-to-know-about-disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes/|website=nerdist.com|publisher=Nerdist|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

All figures, Power Discs and toyboxes, from ''Disney Infinity'' are compatible with ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/forums/read/7.848749-Marvel-Super-Heroes-Unveiled-for-Disney-Infinity-2-0-Edition|title=Marvel Super Heroes Unveiled for Disney Infinity (2.0 Edition)|publisher=The Escapist Magazine|last=Keefer|first=John|date=April 30, 2014 <!-- at 1:45pm --> |accessdate=May 1, 2014}}</ref> Bases from ''Disney Infinity'' are also compatible. However, an [[Xbox 360]] base is not compatible with [[Xbox One]].<ref name=Com/> Whether or not players decide to use the Infinity Base from the first game or second game, that base must be connected to a console via [[USB]].<ref name=Stuff/>

==Characters==
Each character is made to play different from another.<ref name=SDCC/> Many characters were chosen to be included in the game due to popular demand, in which Disney conducted polls on their social networking pages.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity Facebook (Timeline Photo July 21, 2014)|author=[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]|url=https://www.facebook.com/DisneyInfinity/photos/a.490454497671944.128846.417514228299305/770028093047915/?type=1&theater|website=facebook.com|publisher=[[Facebook]]|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> While some characters are playable in a Playset and the Toybox, some are only playable in Toybox mode. Characters are split up into two categories, ''Marvel Super Heroes'' (characters that are based on [[Marvel Entertainment|Marvel]] properties) and ''Disney Originals'' (characters that are based on [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] and [[Pixar]] properties).<ref name=Forbes2>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andyrobertson/2014/06/25/disney-infinity-2-0-release-waves-and-disney-originals/|title='Disney Infinity 2.0' Release Waves And Disney Originals|date=June 25, 2014|accessdate=July 11, 2014|publisher=[[Forbes]]|last=Robertson|first=Andy}}</ref>

