Sam Flynn and Quorra from the [[Tron: Legacy|TRON]] franchise are playable characters exclusive to mobile and PC versions of the game. The announcement was made on February 5, 2015 as the characters are available for purchase on the mobile version and became available for purchase on the PC version during March 2015.<ref name="TRON characters">{{cite web|url=http://diskingdom.com/2015/02/05/disney-infinity-release-digital-exclusive-tron-characters-today/|title=Disney Infinity Release Digital EXCLUSIVE Tron Characters Today!|last=Denman|first=Travis|accessdate=February 5, 2015|publisher=DIS Kingdom}}</ref>

Other characters, including [[M.O.D.O.K.]], [[Mysterio]], [[Doctor Octopus]], [[Luke Cage|Power Man]], [[Black Cat (Marvel Comics)|Black Cat]], [[Carol Danvers|Captain Marvel]], [[Wasp (comics)|Wasp]], [[Sif (comics)|Sif]], [[J. Jonah Jameson]], Cosmo the Spacedog and the [[Collector (comics)|Collector]] appear in the game.<ref name=Guardians/><ref name=Spider>{{cite web|last1=Ching|first1=Albert|title=SPIDER-MAN, VENOM AND MORE ADDED TO "DISNEY INFINITY: MARVEL SUPER HEROES"|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=53340|website=Comic Book Resources|publisher=Comic Book Resources|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/04/30/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-announced|title=Disney Infinity Marvel Super Heroes Announced|accessdate=April 30, 2014|date=April 30, 2014|publisher=[[IGN]]}}</ref> [[War Machine|Iron Patriot]], [[Bucky Barnes|Winter Soldier]], [[Scott Lang|Ant-Man]] and [[White Tiger (comics)|White Tiger]] also appear in the game, but as sidekick characters.<ref name=PowerDiscs>{{cite web|title=2.0 POWER DISCS REVEALED|url=https://infinity.disney.com/en-ca/news/power-disc-1911|website=infinity.disney.com|publisher=[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=GameG>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/guardians-of-the-galaxy-confirmed-for-disney-infin/1100-6421264/|title=Guardians of the Galaxy Confirmed For Disney Infinity|last=Haywald|first=Justin|publisher=Gamespot|date=July 23, 2014|accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Brigante|first1=Ricky|title=Disney Infinity Marvel Super Heroes revealed with "Avengers" characters, play set in Disney Interactive game sequel|url=http://www.insidethemagic.net/2014/04/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-revealed-with-avengers-characters-play-set-in-disney-interactive-game-sequel/|website=Inside the Magic|publisher=Inside the Magic|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref>

Announced in December 2014, Black Suit Spider-Man will be an exclusive sold with the PlayStation Vita Bundle in May 2015. Until it became a single release in the sequel.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity Official Twitter (3:56 PM - 7 Dec 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/541697884589010944|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref>

==Development==

===Concept===
''Disney Infinity'' was originally described to be a "platform that's always growing and will ultimately have something for everyone,"<ref name=Project/> and that the ''Infinity'' platform is open to expanding. When ''Disney Infinity'' was yet to be released, [[Avalanche Software]] CEO, John Blackburn stated that discussions about the inclusion of ''[[Star Wars]]'' and Marvel characters in the game, took place.<ref name=Polygon2>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/1/15/3880346/disney-infinity-star-wars-marvel|title=Disney Infinity developer says Star Wars, Marvel characters under discussion, but not decided|last=McWhertor|first=Michael|date=January 15, 2013 <!-- at 6:06PM --> |accessdate=May 3, 2014|publisher=Polygon}}</ref> On that subject Blackburn said "I hope so! As a developer, I so want that. When Disney bought [[Lucasfilm]], I was like, 'Holy crap! This is awesome!' But at this point in time, there's been some discussions about that, there's just been no decisions made."<ref name=Polygon2/> In February 2014, [[Avalanche Software]] began hiring game testers for a potential ''Disney Infinity'' sequel.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Robertson|first1=Andy|title=Job Listing Suggests Date And Platforms for 'Disney Infinity 2'|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andyrobertson/2014/02/04/disney-infinity-2-release-date-xbox-one-ps4/|website=forbes.com|publisher=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> ''Star Wars'' characters and playsets would eventually be added in the following expansion, ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]''.

Avalanche Software started working with Marvel Entertainment, after it was acquired by Disney in 2009, about developing a game featuring Marvel superheroes, in 2011.<ref name=News2/> The conception of the game started immediately after the acquisition, as ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''{{'}}s executive producer, John Vignocchi commented "As soon as the acquisition happened we started having conversations about Marvel. I giggle that I know the date, because I checked in via [[Foursquare]] at Marvel. So that's how I knew, that was the first time we sat down with [[Joe Quesada]]."<ref name=News2/> Avalanche developed a demo in October 2013, which featured the Marvel superhero Iron Man flying through a rudimentary city.<ref name=News2/> The demo was later released to the public almost a year later.<ref name=News2/>

Since the game was set to include Marvel characters, [[Brian Michael Bendis]], a comic book writer, was brought on to write original story material. This would allow the game's developers to provide more deep and immersive story lines.<ref>{{cite web|author=[[Nintendo]]|title=Nintendo @ E3 - Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes|url=http://e3.nintendo.com/games/wiiu/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-2/|website=nintendo.com|publisher=[[Nintendo]]|accessdate=6 September 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140912103222/http://e3.nintendo.com/games/wiiu/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-2/|archivedate=12 September 2014|df=}}</ref> With a more complex combat system, [[Ninja Theory]] was brought on the development team in February 2014, to fulfill the concept.<ref name=NTK>{{cite web|last1=Fahey|first1=Mike|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Gets Combat Support From Ninja Theory|url=http://kotaku.com/disney-infinity-2-0-gets-combat-support-from-ninja-theo-1629073576|website=kotaku.com|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=31 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=NTP/><ref name=NTG/>

===Announcement===

On April 8, 2014, [[Marvel Entertainment]] released a teaser trailer featuring characters from ''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]'' interacting with Captain America's shield.<ref name=Teaser>{{cite web|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2014/04/08/the-avengers-are-coming-to-disney-infinity|title=The Avengers Are Coming to Disney Infinity|last=Campbell|first=Evan|date=April 8, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=IGN}}</ref> [[D23 (Disney)|D23]], the official Disney fan club, originally reported that the game would be released in August 2014. This statement was later removed, as representatives of the site said "we erroneously reported about the launch of the next chapter of Disney Infinity. This information was incorrect. More news about Disney Infinity will be shared on April 30, and we hope you will check back for that update."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/official-disney-fan-club-says-disney-infinity-2-0-launches-august-2014-then-takes-it-back/1100-6419101/|title=Official Disney fan club says Disney Infinity 2.0 launches August 2014, then takes it back|date=April 20, 2014|last=Maiberg|first=Emanuel|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=May 5, 2014}}</ref>

On April 30, 2014, Disney announced a follow-up game, to ''Disney Infinity'', ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'', at [[Pacific Theatres|Pacific Theatres']] Arc-Light Cinerama Done, in [[Hollywood]],<ref name=CTV/><ref name=Arc/> for release on the [[Xbox 360]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Wii U]], [[iOS]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Xbox One]], and [[PlayStation 4]] in Q4 2014, featuring characters from the [[Marvel Comics]] [[Marvel Universe|universe]]. The announcement was also broadcast live online through a [[webcast]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=725082807542444&set=a.490454497671944.128846.417514228299305&type=1&theater|title=Disney Infinity Facebook - Timeline Photo April 29, 2014|date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=July 13, 2014|author=Disney Infinity|publisher=[[Facebook]]}}</ref> The unveiling included appearances by [[Clark Gregg]], who appears as [[Agent Coulson]] in ''[[Agents of S.H.I.E.L.D.]]'', and [[Samuel L. Jackson]], who appears as [[Ultimate Nick Fury|Nick Fury]] in ''Marvel Super Heroes'' and many films in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]].<ref name=Polygon/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latintimes.com/disney-infinity-20-edition-live-stream-watch-clark-gregg-unveil-new-marvel-update-title-169552|title=‘Disney Infinity’ 2.0 Edition Live Stream: Watch Clark Gregg Unveil New Marvel Update For Title [VIDEO]|accessdate=May 3, 2014|date=April 30, 2014 <!-- at 12:49PM EDT --> |last=Cannon|first=William|publisher=Latin Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.technobuffalo.com/2014/04/30/disney-infinity-2-0-introduces-the-marvel-super-heroes/|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Introduces the Marvel Super Heroes|last=Aune|first=Sean P.|accessdate=July 13, 2014|date=April 30, 2014|publisher=TechnoBuffalo}}</ref> Jackson was in-character as Fury, in a video where he discusses "Project Infinity."<ref name=Project>{{cite web|last1=Rougeau|first1=Mike|title=Everything Marvel Is Willing To Share About The Next Disney Infinity|url=http://www.kotaku.com.au/2014/05/everything-marvel-is-willing-to-share-about-the-next-disney-infinity/|website=kotaku.com.au|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref>

Marvel Entertainment chief creative officer [[Joe Quesada]] was also at the unveiling, declaring that the comic book characters are "uniquely Marvel but still fit within the game".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/wireStory/disney-adding-marvel-heroes-infinity-game-23534582|title=Disney Adding Marvel Heroes to 'Infinity' Game|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC News]]|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=May 3, 2014}}</ref> At [[Sony]]'s [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] 2014 conference it was revealed that the game would be released for the [[PlayStation Vita]] and [[PlayStation TV]], in 2015.<ref name=Vita>{{cite web|last1=Kubba|first1=Sinan|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 announced for Vita, Vita TV|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/06/09/disney-infinity-2-0-announced-for-vita-vita-tv/|website=Joystiq|publisher=Joystiq|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> The PlayStation Vita version of the game will play like the PlayStation 3 version.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 on Vita To Be "Just Like The PS3 Version"|url=http://thevitalounge.net/disney-infinity-2-0-on-vita-to-be-just-like-the-ps3-version/|website=thevitalounge.net|publisher=The Vita Lounge|last=Gruetzmacher|first=Brad|accessdate=26 July 2014}}</ref> The ''Guardians of the Galaxy'' Playset was revealed on July 23, 2014, and it was confirmed Studio Gobo (the studio that developed the ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean]]'' Playset for ''Disney Infinity'') developed the Playset.<ref name=Gobo>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2014-07/23/guardians-of-the-galaxy-disney-infinity|title=UK studio shrinks Guardians of the Galaxy for Disney Infinity|last=Robertson|first=Andy|date=July 23, 2014|accessdate=July 23, 2014|publisher=Wired}}</ref>

===Design===
[[File:Black Widow Character Design Stages in Disney Infinity Marvel Super Heroes.jpg|thumb|right|The design stages of the ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' character [[Black Widow (Natalia Romanova)|Black Widow]].]]
The art style from ''Disney Infinity'', in which every character and object is designed to look like a [[toy]] and was co-designed by [[Pixar]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hoggins|first1=Tom|title=Disney Infinity: John Vignocchi interview|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/video-games/10106113/Disney-Infinity-John-Vignocchi-interview.html|website=telegraph.co.uk|publisher=Telegraph|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> was carried over to ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''. Developers re-imagined Marvel characters in art style. John Vignocchi said on the redesigns, "it was a really interesting process. Working with Joe Quesada and the creative team and Marvel -- getting them to understand what the visual aesthetic of 'Disney Infinity' is, that is, they're not the characters themselves, but toy versions of those characters, and reimagining some of Marvel's most iconic superheroes in that art style was a daunting, but very fun task for this team."<ref name=Wonder/> Each character goes through multiple stages of development, including how they will look in the game and what their figurine's pose will be.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=735097293207662&set=a.490454497671944.128846.417514228299305&type=1&theater|title=Disney Infinity Facebook - Timeline Photo May 18, 2014|date=May 18, 2014|accessdate=July 13, 2014|publisher=[[Facebook]]|author=Disney Infinity}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=729454677105257&set=a.490454497671944.128846.417514228299305&type=1&theater|title=Disney Infinity Facebook - Timeline Photo May 7, 2014|date=May 7, 2014|accessdate=July 13, 2014|publisher=[[Facebook]]|author=Disney Infinity}}</ref> The developers specifically designed the Venom character to be on par with Hulk when it came to size and mass. On Venom's design John Vignocchi said "we hulked him out a bit. in fact, the character is the only one that comes close to the Incredible Hulk in the game (designers wanted another brute to offer) and when fully powered up, stands on equal footing with the green beast."<ref name=Herald/>

No "Crystal" variants of characters have been designed for ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'', unlike the first game.<ref name=Wonder/> The ''Disney Infinity'' team wanted to focus on a more diverse array of characters, as said by John Vignocchi "we're not planning on doing the crystal characters again. Our focus this time around – rather than create a whole series of chase characters, we wanted to make sure that we had a wider variety of characters," he said. "What we decided to do instead was really put our horsepower into creating different characters as opposed to variants. We think our fans appreciate having a character like Star-Lord or Rocket Raccoon as opposed to another version of [[Mickey Mouse]]."<ref name=Wonder/> The game has been designed to be less violent, in order to appeal to a wider audience.<ref name=Nerdist/> Despite this, a Crystal variation of [[Fantasia (1940 film)|Sorcerer's Apprentice]] Mickey Mouse will be released.<ref name=CMM>{{cite web|last1=Hare|first1=Chris|title=Crystal Micky Mouse Coming to Disney Infinity 2.0|url=http://connecteddigitalworld.com/2014/08/18/crystal-micky-mouse-coming-disney-infinity-2-0/|website=connecteddigitalworld.com|publisher=Connected Digital World|accessdate=24 August 2014}}</ref>

When designing the game, Avalanche Software focused not only on the inclusion of the [[near field communication|NFC-enabled]]<ref name=NFC/> Marvel figurines, but improving the Toybox mode (especially for younger players) as well.<ref name=Joystiq>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/04/30/disney-infinity-2-0-edition-featuring-marvel-super-heroes-coming/|title=Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes coming this fall; PS4 and Xbox One joining the fight|accessdate=May 1, 2014|date=April 30, 2014|last=de Matos|first=Xav|publisher=Joystiq}}</ref> Jimmy Pitaro, president of [[Disney Interactive Studios]] stated "we wanted to take everything that worked so well and make it epic."<ref name=CTV/> Each character was picked based on how they would fit in the game, as said by TQ Jefferson, "what you're going to see as we roll out and reveal more characters, is that they're going to be more characters that you've known forever and they make sense," Jefferson said. "And the other characters, you may not know them as well, but once you see them in-game, you're going to understand why we made the choices that we made. These characters bring a certain narrative strength with them and, just as important, they bring a unique bit of gameplay with them ... [these are the] characters that are the most fun to play ... that have the most impact on story. Once you see the full spectrum of characters, it's not just an Avengers game. It's very much a Marvel super heroes game."<ref name=RAM/>

The development team tried to appeal to the game's target audience (children) by making changes to environments, with one being to disregard physics.<ref name=Webs/> Matt Solie, of Disney Interactive Studios, when asked about the topic stated "I had my nephews, who are eight and five, try ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man 2 (2014 video game)|Amazing Spider-Man 2]]'', which is the epitome of physics-based, buildings attached—[it's] not really fun for them. They didn't understand, 'Why can't I swing?'" Solie said. "It just made sense for a kids and family game."<ref name=Webs/> Also basing the game around its target audience, John Blackburn part of the game's development team, looked to his 6 year old nephew, Logan, to see what younger audiences wanted out of the game.<ref name=News2/> The procedural editing options were added, after Blackburn noticed that Logan was building very simple things in the Toybox.<ref name=News2/>

Though ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' is heavily inspired by ''[[Avengers Assemble (TV series)|Avengers Assemble]]'', ''[[Ultimate Spider-Man (TV series)|Ultimate Spider-Man]]'', ''[[Hulk and the Agents of S.M.A.S.H.]]'' and the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] in terms of design, the possibility of the [[Alternate versions of Thor#Thor|female Thor]] from the comics joining the game has not been ruled out.<ref name=Female>{{cite web|last1=Martin|first1=Liam|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 'not ruling out inclusion of female Thor'|url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/gaming/news/a584603/disney-infinity-20-not-ruling-out-inclusion-of-female-thor.html#~oNT3FyghNPokSB|website=digitalspy.ca|publisher=Digital Spy|accessdate=24 August 2014}}</ref> On the possibility of the game's artists possibly designing a toy-like female Thor, John Vignocchi stated "The Thor that we have inside of Infinity is based on the animated series Avengers Assemble. Infinity being a platform that evolves over time, that certainly doesn't rule out the possibility of creating a new version of Thor. Should there be a demand, we'd love to do that."<ref name=Female/> No [[X-Men]] characters will be included in the game.<ref name=XMen>{{cite web|last1=Ponce|first1=Tony|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Won't Include X-Men Characters|url=http://www.gameranx.com/updates/id/23996/article/disney-infinity-2-0-won-t-include-x-men-characters/|website=gameranx.com|publisher=[[Complex (magazine)|Gameranx]]|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref> Analysts believe this is due to the fact that [[20th Century Fox]] owns the film rights to X-Men.<ref name=XMen/>

The ''Disney Infinity'' fanbase and "community" have avidly played a role in development of ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''. Community members Stewart "CrazybyNick" Malcolm, Patrick "PapaEcho" Efird, Tyler "Tyforce" Cole, Jose "doctorlogicgate" Abalos and Quinn "quinnjitsu" Johnson, who competed in multiple challenges hosted by the ''Disney Infinity'' team, were actually hired to create free downloadable levels for ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''.<ref name=TV/><ref name=VB/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Barnes|first1=Brooks|title=Disney Infinity Game Studio Hires a Top Player to Create Toy Box Levels|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/15/business/media/disney-infinity-game-studio-hires-a-top-player-to-create-toy-box-levels.html?_r=0|website=nytimes.com|publisher=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>

[[Ninja Theory]] was hired by Disney to design Loki, Ronan, Green Goblin and Jasmine's combat systems and polish all of the other characters' combat systems.<ref name=NTK/><ref name=NTP>{{cite web|last1=S. Good|first1=Owen|title=Heavenly Sword studio Ninja Theory is working on Disney Infinity 2.0|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/8/31/6089529/heavenly-sword-studio-ninja-theory-is-working-on-disney-infinity-2-0|website=polygon.com|publisher=Polygon|accessdate=31 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=NTG>{{cite web|last1=Reeves|first1=Ben|title=Heavenly Sword And DmC Dev Helping With Disney Infinity 2.0|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2014/08/31/heavenly-sword-and-dmc-dev-helping-with-disney-infinity-2-0.aspx|website=gameinformer.com|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=31 August 2014}}</ref>

===PlayStation 4 and Xbox One development===
Prior to the release of ''Disney Infinity'', [[Avalanche Software]] expressed interest in supporting ''Disney Infinity'' toys on [[Xbox One]] and [[PlayStation 4]] consoles. John Day, of Avalanche Software stated that Xbox One and PlayStation 4 versions of ''Disney Infinity'' would likely be "way more beautiful," offer "a whole lot more" content, "or both."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/gaming/news/a500519/disney-infinity-toys-reader-to-work-for-years-to-come.html  |title='Disney Infinity' toys, reader to work "for years to come" |last=Reynolds |first=Matthew |publisher=[[DigitalSpy]]|accessdate=August 15, 2014}}</ref>

The versions of the game for the PlayStation 4 and the Xbox One have better graphics and more memory than their counterparts for the PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, and Wii U.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/490176558754435072|title=Disney Infinity Official Twitter (9:49 AM - 18 Jul 2014 Tweet)|date=July 18, 2014|accessdate=July 20, 2014|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Disney Infinity}}</ref> When discussing the additional power of the PlayStation 4 and the Xbox One, John Vignocchi stated "I’d say, specifically related to Xbox One, the graphical prowess of that system is incredible. So, we’re looking at what we can do to make sure the game looks incredible on [the Xbox One]. From a features perspective, I’d say the thing we’re most excited about is that players are going to be able to create Toy Boxes now that are much, much larger than they were before,"<ref name=TV/> and "In terms of what we're doing with [PS4 and Xbox One], we're planning on making use of the graphical prowess of those machines — they can pump out some amazing-looking graphics. In addition to that, what we're planning on doing is taking advantage of the overall memory footprint. In Disney Infinity there were certain platforms that were constrained by the amount of [[Random-access memory|RAM]], so people couldn't truly build the toy box of their dreams. We've optimized the engine to allow the last-gen, PS3 and 360, to still build compelling Toy Box levels, but with Xbox One and PS4, the sky's the limit."<ref name=RAM>{{cite web|last1=McWhertor|first1=Michael|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes is 'not just an Avengers game'|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/4/30/5669802/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-the-avengers|website=polygon.com|publisher=Polygon|accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> The Xbox One and PlayStation 4 versions of the game are more advanced than the others, as executive producer John Vignocchi said "one of the most unique features of ''Disney Infinity 2.0'' on Xbox One and PlayStation 4, just because of the memory footprint of those systems, is that the size of the toy boxes you can create are just gigantic."<ref name=CTV/> The game engine is improved and expanded.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes Set to Punch Crime Right in the Gut|url=http://news.xbox.com/2014/04/games-disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes|website=news.xbox.com|publisher=Xbox Wire|accessdate=1 August 2014|author=Xbox Wire Staff}}</ref>

==Release==
''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' (which also has been marketed for release as ''Disney Infinity 2.0'', ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes (2.0 Edition)'' and ''Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes'')<ref name=Marvel>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/video_games/2014/5/2/22457/enter_the_world_of_disney_infinity_marvel_super_heroes|title=Enter the World of Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes|publisher=[[Marvel Entertainment]]|accessdate=May 5, 2014|date=May 2, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Polygon/><ref name=Forbes>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andyrobertson/2014/04/30/disney-infinity-2-0-marvel-super-heroes-announced/|title=Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes Announced|date=April 30, 2014 <!-- at 2:30PM --> |accessdate=May 1, 2014|last=Robertson|first=Andy|publisher=[[Forbes]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/4/8/5594018/disney-infinity-marvel-avengers-teaser|title=Marvel teases Avengers in Disney Infinity '2.0 Edition'|date=April 8, 2014 <!-- at 12:36pm --> |accessdate=May 1, 2014|last=Sarkar|first=Samit|publisher=Polygon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playstationlifestyle.net/2014/04/30/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-announced-by-disney-for-ps4-ps3/|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes Announced by Disney for PS4 & PS3|last=Dunning|first=Jason|publisher=PlayStation LifeStyle}}</ref> game disc and video game software will be released to the public on multiple dates, through "Starter Packs." Starter Packs are bundles that will provide players with the game disc, the Infinity Base, a web code card, a poster and varying playable characters based on the Starter Pack they purchase.

The game was first released in the ''Marvel Super Heroes'' Starter Pack, which includes the game disc, the Infinity Base, the [[Avengers (comics)|Avengers]] Playset, a web code card, a poster as well as [[Iron Man]], [[Black Widow (Natalia Romanova)|Black Widow]] and [[Thor (Marvel Comics)|Thor]] playable characters.<ref name=Kotaku>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/disney-infinity-marvel-superheroes-coming-this-fall-1569867532|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Superheroes Coming This Fall|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=April 30, 2014}}</ref> This bundle was released on September 23, 2014 in [[North America]], September 19, 2014 in the [[United Kingdom]], and on September 18, 2014 in [[Australasia]] and the rest of [[Europe]], on PlayStation 3, PlayStation 4, Wii U, Xbox 360 and Xbox One.<ref name=AUS/><ref name=EU/><ref name=Achieve/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/07/24/disney-infinity-2-0-hits-north-america-on-september-23/|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 hits North America on September 23.0|last=Kubba|first=Sinan|publisher=Joystiq|date=July 24, 2014|accessdate=July 24, 2014}}</ref>

The ''Toy Box'' Starter Pack (known as the ''Toybox Combo'' Starter Pack in some markets),<ref name=Combo>{{cite web|last1=Robertson|first1=Andy|title=New 'Disney Infinity 2.0' Toy Box Pack Reveals 'Big Hero 6' Characters|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andyrobertson/2014/08/18/new-disney-infinity-2-0-toy-box-pack-reveals-big-hero-6-characters/|website=forbes.com|publisher=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> was released on November 4, 2014 in North America and November 7, 2014 in the United Kingdom,<ref name=Combo/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Suszek|first1=Mike|title=Disney Infinity 2.0's Toy Box pack stars Stitch, Merida|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/08/18/disney-infinity-2-0s-toy-box-pack-stars-stitch-merida/|website=joystiq.com|publisher=Joystiq|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> includes the game disc, Merida and Stitch playable characters, two Toybox Game Discs, the Infinity Base, a web code card and a poster.<ref name=TBI>{{cite web|last1=Futter|first1=Mike|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Gets Toy Box Starter Pack This November|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2014/08/18/disney-infinity-2-0-gets-toy-box-starter-pack-this-november.aspx|website=gameinformer.com|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=Leak>{{cite web|last1=D.|first1=Travis|title=Walmart Disney Infinity Update Confirms Rumors, Brings Forth More Questions|url=http://vinylmationkingdom.com/2014/06/11/walmart-disney-infinity-update-confirms-rumors-brings-forth-questions/|website=Vinylmation Kingdom|publisher=Vinylmation Kingdom|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fahey|first1=Mike|title=Stich And Merida Star In The Other Way To Buy Disney Infinity 2.0|url=http://kotaku.com/stich-and-merida-star-in-the-other-way-to-buy-disney-in-1623216899|website=kotaku.com|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> This bundle will be released for PlayStation 3, PlayStation 4, Wii U, Xbox 360 and Xbox One.<ref name=TBI/>

A ''Collector's Edition'' Starter Pack was exclusive to the [[PlayStation 3]] and [[PlayStation 4]] released, and in addition to everything included in the ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' Starter Pack, it includes the [[Hulk]], [[Captain America]] and [[Hawkeye (comics)|Hawkeye]] as playable characters and a diorama featuring a Frost Beast to display all ''The Avengers'' characters.<ref name=Forbes2/><ref name=Sony>{{cite web|last1=Jackson|first1=Leah B.|title=DISNEY INFINITY / 9 JUN 2014 E3 2014: SONY ANNOUNCES EXCLUSIVE MARVEL DISNEY INFINITY CONTENT|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/06/10/e3-2014-sony-announces-exclusive-marvel-disney-infinity-content|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2014-06/11/disney-infinity-2-e3|title=Hands-on with Disney Infinity's new Marvel characters at E3|last=Robertson|first=Andy|publisher=Wired|accessdate=July 20, 2014|date=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=Collect>{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/07/22/hulk-smash-disney-infinity-marvel-2-0-on-ps4-ps3/|title=Hulk smash Disney Infinity: Marvel 2.0 on PS4, PS3|last=Conditt|first=Jessica|publisher=[[Joystiq]]|date=July 23, 2014|accessdate=July 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Giardina|first1=Carolyn|title=Sony PlayStation, Disney Debut Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes Collector's Edition|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/behind-screen/sony-playstation-disney-debut-disney-720456|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=22 July 2014|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> The ''Collector's Edition'' was unveiled during [[Sony]]'s [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3 2014]] press conference, and was created after a partnership between Sony and Disney was formed.<ref name=Sony/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Prell|first1=Sam|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Collector's Edition exclusive to PlayStation|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/06/09/disney-infinity-2-0-collectors-edition-comes-to-ps4-first/|website=Joystiq|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> The ''Collector's Edition'' is exclusive to [[EB Games]] in [[Australia]] and [[New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wildgoose|first1=David|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 collectors edition is exclusive to EB Games, PlayStation|url=http://www.mcvpacific.com/news/read/disney-infinity-2-0-collectors-edition-is-exclusive-to-eb-games-playstation/0135731|website=mcvpacific.com|publisher=MCV Pacific|accessdate=26 July 2014}}</ref> This bundle was released on September 23, 2014 in North America, September 19, 2014 in the United Kingdom, and on September 18, 2014 in Australasia and the rest of Europe.

The game was bundled with a 12 GB [[PlayStation 3]] console.<ref name=Collect/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fahey|first1=Mike|title=HULK HATES BEING TIMED PLAYSTATION EXCLUSIVE|url=http://kotaku.com/hulk-hates-being-timed-playstation-exclusive-1609272465|website=kotaku.com|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> An ''Disney Infinity 2.0 Marvel Premium Value Pack'' bundle exclusive to [[Amazon.com]] includes the ''Marvel Super Heroes'' Starter Pack, Captain America, Venom and Rocket Raccoon playable characters, a Power Disc blind pack and the ''Spider-Man'' Playset.{{citation needed|date=October 2015}}

For those who purchased the first game, ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' will also be released digitally,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/490579365798109184|title=Disney Infinity Official Twitter (12:30 PM - 19 Jul 2014 Tweet)|date=July 19, 2014|accessdate=July 20, 2014|publisher=[[Twitter]]|author=Disney Infinity}}</ref> through the [[Nintendo eShop]], [[PlayStation Store]], and [[Xbox Games Store]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity Twitter (9:12 AM - 13 Aug 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/499589233540349952|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> The digital version of the game will not be available for [[Xbox One]], due to hardware incompatibility issues.<ref name=INCX>{{cite web|last1=Vignocchi|first1=John|title=John Vignocchi Twitter (8:52 AM - 24 Jul 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/JohnVignocchi/status/492336593001127936|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> The digital version of ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' will not be available at launch, but instead will be released on November 4, 2014 in North America.<ref name=Combo/><ref name=Digital>{{cite web|last1=Vignocchi|first1=John|title=John Vignocchi Twitter (10:01 AM - 13 Sep 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/JohnVignocchi/status/510835596378378240|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Suszek|first1=Mike|title=Disney Infinity's Toy Box 2.0 offered as standalone download|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/09/15/disney-infinitys-toy-box-2-0-offered-as-standalone-download/|website=joystiq.com|publisher=Joystiq|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> This version of the game includes the Toybox mode, but requires an Infinity Base and ''Disney Infinity'' figurines.<ref name=Digital/>

The [[Microsoft Windows]] version of the game will be released digitally, as a standalone, brand new application for Windows.<ref name=WIND>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity Tweet (8:41 AM - 12 Aug 2014)|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/499219127865966592|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> [[Micropayment|Micro transactions]] will be required to unlock additional content.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity Twitter (7:38 PM - 12 Aug 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/499384425235644417|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> The [[iOS]] version of ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' will be released through the [[App Store (iOS)|Apple App Store]].

Disney Interactive Studios announced that starting July 24, 2014 through September 22, 2014, consumers who pre-order the Starter Pack will receive a free ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' figurine from retailers nationwide.<ref name=Shop/> Retailers including [[Disney Store]], [[Tesco]] and [[Game (retailer)|Game]] have offered this deal.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Scammell|first1=David|title=Free Disney Infinity 2 character when you pre-order|url=http://www.videogamer.com/ps4/disney_infinity_20_marvel_super_heroes/news/free_disney_infinity_2_character_when_you_pre-order.html|website=videogamer.com|publisher=Videogamer}}</ref>

==Marketing==
[[Disney Interactive Studios]] has been present at multiple conventions (including the [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]]<ref>{{cite web|last1=Slesinger|first1=Scott|title=Disney Interactive Shines at E3|url=https://thewaltdisneycompany.com/blog/disney-interactive-shines-e3|website=thewaltdisneycompany.com|publisher=[[The Walt Disney Company]]|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> and [[San Diego Comic-Con International]]),<ref>{{cite web|author=Disney Infinity|title=Disney Infinity Twitter (8:00 PM - 22 Jul 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/491779749958942721|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> promoting ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''. Free figures were handed out at E3 2014, and at Blogger Bash's Sweet Suite 2014.<ref name=Blogger>{{cite web|url=http://vinylmationkingdom.com/2014/07/19/disney-infinity-blogger-bashs-sweet-suite-2014/|title=Disney Infinity at Blogger Bash’s Sweet Suite 2014|last=D.|first=Travis|publisher=Vinylmation Kingdom|accessdate=July 20, 2014|date=July 19, 2014}}</ref> In promotion of both ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' and ''[[Big Hero 6 (film)|Big Hero 6]]'', Disney created a giant sized version of the [[Baymax]] ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' figure.<ref name=Baymax>{{cite web|url=http://screenburn.kotaku.com/disney-infinity-baymax-from-big-hero-6-1609856466|title=Disney Infinity Baymax From Big Hero 6|last=Struan|first=John|date=July 23, 2014|accessdate=July 24, 2014|publisher=[[Kotaku]]}}</ref><ref name=Bay>{{cite web|last1=Vignocchi|first1=John|title=John Vignocchi Twitter (10:05 AM - 25 Jul 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/JohnVignocchi/status/492717282842267648|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> At San Diego Comic-Con Disney set up a [[pop-up shop]], which allowed the public to play the game, meet special guests and participate in giveaways.<ref name=Shop>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes (2.0 Edition) Set to Hit North American Retail Stores On September 23|url=http://www.disneyinteractive.com/news/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-2-0-edition-set-to-hit-north-american-retail-stores-on-september-23/|website=disneyinteractive.com|publisher=[[Disney Interactive Studios]]|accessdate=26 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=Convention>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes (2.0 Edition) Heads to San Diego During Comic-Con Week|url=http://www.disneyinteractive.com/news/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-comic-con-2014/|website=disneyinteractive.com|publisher=[[Disney Interactive Studios]]|accessdate=26 July 2014}}</ref> [[Alex Hirsch]], creator of ''[[Gravity Falls]]'' was also present at the pop-up shop, to announce the inclusion of ''Gravity Falls'' Power Discs.<ref>{{cite web|title=Vacation to Gravity Falls, Oregon, with New Disney Infinity 2.0 Power Discs!|url=http://www.disneyinteractive.com/news/vacation-to-gravity-falls-oregon-with-new-disney-infinity-2-0-power-discs/|website=disneyinteractive.com|publisher=Disney Interactive Studios|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref>  Disney also hosted special events for [[D23 (Disney)|D23]] and [[Marvel Unlimited]] members.<ref name=Convention/> The game was also present during the Marvel Games panel.<ref name=Convention/> Additionally the Marvel Booth and [[Microsoft]] Game Lounge held demos, to promote the game.<ref name=Convention/> A ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''-themed Xbox One was also given away at Comic-Con.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ohannessian|first1=Kevin|title=Win Xbox One consoles with custom art from Microsoft's Comic-Con contest|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/11277/20140725/xbox-one-microsoft-custom-console.htm|website=techtimes.com|publisher=Tech Times|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref>

On August 9, 2014 [[GameStop]] held ''Disney Infinity Day'', an event that celebrates the game in stores, by offering promotions on it.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lada|first1=Jenni|title=August 9, 2014 is a GameStop Disney Infinity Day|url=http://www.technologytell.com/gaming/133253/august-9-2014-gamestop-disney-infinity-day/|website=technologytell.com|publisher=Technology Tell|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> An official ''Disney Infinity Toy Box Summit'' will be held from August 15, 2014 to August 17, 2014 in [[Salt Lake City]].<ref name=Summit>{{cite web|last1=Farokhmanesh|first1=Megan|title=Disney Infinity Toy Box Summit will test Toy Box designers' skills|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/6/27/5851122/disney-infinity-toy-box-summit-will-test-toy-box-designers-skills|website=polygon.com|publisher=Polygon|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> The summit will be a fan appreciation event and will allow invitees to participate in multiple competitions involving the Toybox.<ref name=Summit/> Disney will also allow invitees to have a hands-on preview with ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''.<ref name=Summit/> An in-depth look at the Toybox will also be showcased during the Summit.<ref>{{cite web|title=WATCH TOY BOX SUMMIT LIVE|url=https://infinity.disney.com/en-ca/news/countdown-to-toy-box-1732|website=infinity.disney.com|publisher=Disney Infinity|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Disney also held a "Movie Magic Video Contest," which gave players a chance to win a Captain America figure and a chance to go to the Toybox Summit.<ref>{{cite web|title=MOVIE MAGIC VIDEO CONTEST|url=https://infinity.disney.com/en-ca/news/movie-magic-video-1514|website=infinity.disney.com|publisher=Disney Infinity|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' was included in Disney's "Marvel Super Hero September" campaign, which promoted multiple Marvel films and products, including ''[[Captain America: The Winter Soldier]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Graser|first1=Marc|title=‘Marvel Super Hero September’ Puts Spotlight on Characters Outside Theaters|url=https://variety.com/2014/biz/news/marvel-super-hero-september-promotion-1201296045/|website=variety.com|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref>

Multiple trailers have been released for the game. A teaser was released on April 8, 2014.<ref name=Teaser/> The reveal trailer for the game was unveiled on April 30, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=ANNOUNCING MARVEL SUPER HEROES|url=https://infinity.disney.com/en-ca/news/announcing-marvel-super-1156|website=infinity.disney.com|publisher=Disney Infinity|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> A trailer focusing on the Avengers Playset was released on May 22, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/5/22/5741348/disney-infinity-2-0-trailer-the-avengers|title=Watch the Hulk parallel park in this Disney Infinity trailer|last=Corriea|first=Alexa Ray|accessdate=May 24, 2014|date=May 22, 2014|publisher=Polygon}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/andyrobertson/2014/05/22/disney-infinity-avengers-play-set-trailer/|title='Disney Infinity 2.0' Avengers Trailer Reveals Loki's Chilling Plans|last=Robertson|first=Andy|publisher=[[Forbes]]|date=May 22, 2014|accessdate=May 24, 2014}}</ref> A second trailer this time based on the Spider-Man Playset was released on June 10, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 2014: Spider-Man Play Set Announced for Disney Infinity 2.0|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/gamenews.php?id=119366|website=comingsoon.net|publisher=Comingsoon.net|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> Disney revealed Stitch and Tinker Bell with a preview of the game, on July 16, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=MISCHIEF MEETS MAGIC|url=https://infinity.disney.com/en-ca/news/mischief-meets-1583|website=infinity.disney.com|publisher=Disney Infinity|accessdate=13 August 2014}}</ref> Another trailer focusing on the Guardians of the Galaxy Playset was released on July 23, 2014<ref>{{cite web|author=Disney Infinity|title=DEFEND THE GALAXY|url=https://infinity.disney.com/en-ca/news/1619|website=infinity.disney.com|publisher=Disney Infinity|accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> A trailer centering on super villains ([[Loki (comics)|Loki]], [[Ronan the Accuser|Ronan]] and [[Green Goblin]]) was shown at San Diego Comic-Con 2014 on July 26, 2014, and was released to the public on July 28, 2014.<ref name=IGNVillains>{{cite web|last1=Karmali|first1=Luke|title=LOKI, GREEN GOBLIN AND RONAN HEADED TO DISNEY INFINITY 2.0|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2014/07/29/loki-green-goblin-and-ronan-headed-to-disney-infinity-20|website=ign.com|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=30 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Fahey|first1=Mike|title=Meanwhile, In Disney Infinity 2.0, super villains  Attack|url=http://kotaku.com/meanwhile-in-disney-infinity-2-0-super-villains-attac-1611966858|website=kotaku.com|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|accessdate=30 July 2014}}</ref> On August 7, 2014 a trailer focusing on [[Aladdin (Disney character)|Aladdin]] and [[Princess Jasmine|Jasmine]] from ''[[Aladdin (1992 Disney film)|Aladdin]]'' was released.<ref name=IGNA>{{cite web|last1=Karmali|first1=Luke|title=ALADDIN AND JASMINE JOIN DISNEY INFINITY 2.0|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2014/08/07/aladdin-and-jasmine-join-disney-infinity-20|website=ign.com|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> To coincide [[Gamescom#Gamescom 2014|Gamescom 2014]], Disney Interactive Studios released a trailer featuring [[Donald Duck]] on August 12, 2014.<ref name=Donald>{{cite web|last1=Crecente|first1=Brian|title=Donald Duck joins Disney Infinity 2.0|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/8/12/5994165/donald-duck-joins-disney-infinity-2-0|website=polygon.com|publisher=Polygon|accessdate=12 August 2014}}</ref> An informational trailer for the Toybox was released on August 14, 2014.<ref name=14Aug>{{cite web|last1=Kato|first1=Matthew|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes The Toy Box Is Easier Than Ever|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/disney_infinity_marvel_super_heroes/b/xboxone/archive/2014/08/14/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-toy-box-is-easier-than-ever.aspx|website=gameinformer.com|publisher=Game Informer|accessdate=14 August 2014}}</ref> Another trailer centering on the Toybox was released on August 20, 2014.<ref name=TA20>{{cite web|title=ANNOUNCING: TOY BOX STARTER PACK|url=https://infinity.disney.com/en-ca/news/announcing--toy-box-starter-1779|website=infinity.disney.com|publisher=[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref> A trailer revolving around Baymax and Hiro Hamada from ''Big Hero 6'' was released on August 27, 2014.<ref name=H6IGN>{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Katie|title=BIG HERO 6 CHARACTERS HEADED TO DISNEY INFINITY 2.0|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2014/08/27/big-hero-6-characters-headed-to-disney-infinity-20?watch|website=ign.com|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Graser|first1=Marc|title=‘Big Hero 6′ Gets to Play with the Big Boys in ‘Disney Infinity’|url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/news/big-hero-6-gets-to-play-with-the-big-boys-in-disney-infinity-1201291836/|website=variety.com|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Siegel|first1=Lucas|title=BIG HERO 6 Comes to DISNEY INFINITY 2.0: Hiro and Baymax Officially Revealed|url=http://www.newsarama.com/21977-big-hero-6-comes-to-disney-infinity-2-0-hiro-and-baymax-officially-revealed.html|website=newsarama.com|publisher=[[Newsarama]]|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> A trailer, titled Walk It, themed to the [[Aerosmith]] song [[Walk This Way]] was released on September 5, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 video – "Walk It"|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/disney-infinity-2-0-video-walk-it/|website=nintendoeverything.com|publisher=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=6 September 2014}}</ref>

Multiple teases from the ''Disney Infinity'' team have been made on social networks, including [[Twitter]] and [[Facebook]]. One prime example is the "Something wicked is coming to #DisneyInfinity... pic.twitter.com/tt8sJytvwi" tweet, which revealed [[Maleficent]] would appear in the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity Twitter (9:15 AM - 12 May 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/465887882331557888|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=24 July 2014|author=Disney Infinity}}</ref> To promote the game, developers have appeared in interviews conducted by gaming sites, including [[GameSpot]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vignocchi|first1=John|title=John Vignocchi Tweet (10:23 AM - 24 Jul 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/JohnVignocchi/status/492359501660434432|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> Disney has also chosen to advertise the game through [[Radio Disney]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity Twitter (4:07 PM - 24 Jul 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/492445876150075392|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=25 July 2014|author=Disney Infinity}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Tompkins|first1=Morgan|title=Morgan Tompkins Twitter (4:13 PM - 24 Jul 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/MorganTompkins/status/492447452415660032|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref> A weekly web series, ''The Disney Infinity Toy Box TV: The Official Weekly Web Show'', which highlights outstanding Toy Box creations from players,<ref name=TV>{{cite web|title=An Interview with Disney's Real Marvel Super Heroes|url=http://news.xbox.com/2014/05/games-marvel-super-heroes-interview|website=news.xbox.com|publisher=Xbox Wire|accessdate=25 July 2014|author=Xbox Wire Staff}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Seedhouse|first1=Alex|title=New Disney Infinity Toy Box TV episode is a Comic-Con Special|url=http://www.nintendo-insider.com/2014/08/02/new-disney-infinity-toy-box-tv-episode-comic-con-special/|website=nintendo-insider.com|publisher=Nintendo Insider|accessdate=2 August 2014}}</ref> has regularly been providing updates on the game.<ref name=NI/> These updates include "sneak peeks" at characters (in depth descriptions of characters' abilities and appearances.)<ref name=NI/><ref>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity Twitter (10:15 AM - 25 Jul 2014 Tweet)|url=https://twitter.com/DisneyInfinity/status/492719686845734912|website=twitter.com|publisher=[[Twitter]]|accessdate=25 July 2014|author=Disney Infinity}}</ref> The web show is hosted John Vignocchi and the game's community manager Allison Petrek.<ref name=VB>{{cite web|last1=Valdes|first1=Giancarlo|title=How five Disney Infinity superfans turned their passion into level-design gigs|url=https://venturebeat.com/2014/08/20/how-five-disney-infinity-superfans-turned-their-passion-into-level-design-gigs/|website=venturebeat.com|publisher=Venture beat|accessdate=20 August 2014}}</ref>

In a marketing stunt, a holographic visualization of Hulk was projected at [[Tower Bridge]].<ref name=TowerBridge>{{cite web|last1=Marley|first1=Scott|title=Watch as The Hulk raises Tower Bridge for Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/entertainment/video-games/video-games-news/hulk-raises-tower-bridge-disney-4263572|website=dailyrecord.co.uk|publisher=Daily Record|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=LiftTower/> The projection of Hulk stood 36 feet high, and after debuting the stunt, Disney officially uploaded a video of the hologram on [[YouTube]].<ref name=TowerBridge/><ref name=LiftTower/> The stunt also featured holographic projections of Spider-Man and Iron Man.<ref name=LiftTower>{{cite web|title=Hulk Lifts Up Tower Bridge (For 'Disney Infinity 2.0')|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/09/15/disney-infinity-hulk-tower-bridge_n_5821018.html|website=huffingtonpost.co.uk|publisher=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>

Since the game's unveiling there have been multiple leaks revealing content featured within ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'', primarily from stores marketing the game. [[Target Corporation|Target]] inattentively leaked the release date of the game, September 23, 2014, in a flyer.<ref name=TargetLeaks>{{cite web|title=Target leaks release date, Venom for Disney Infinity 2.0|url=http://nintendoeverything.com/target-leaks-release-date-venom-for-disney-infinity-2-0/|website=Nintendo Everything|publisher=Nintendo Everything|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> [[Venom (Marvel Comics character)|Venom]] was also leaked by the flyer, as the character had never been revealed prior.<ref name=TargetLeaks/> [[Walmart]] later leaked that multiple characters including the [[Guardians of the Galaxy (2008 team)|Guardians of the Galaxy]] would be playable in the game. Walmart did so by listing multiple characters, Playset packs and Starter Packs on their website.<ref name=Leak/><ref name=Leak2>{{cite web|title=TINKERBELL, DONALD DUCK, STITCH, AND MUCH MORE LEAKED BY WALMART|url=http://infinityinquirer.com/2014/06/11/tinkerbell-donald-duck-stitch-and-much-more-leaked-by-walmart/|website=[[Walmart|Walmart.com]]|publisher=Infinity Inquirer|accessdate=13 June 2014}}</ref> Another image was leaked, showcasing [[Star-Lord]] and [[Gamora]] figures.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://screenburn.kotaku.com/disney-infinity-star-lord-and-gamora-figures-1601254079|title=Disney Infinity Star-Lord and Gamora Figures|last=Struan|first=John|publisher=[[Kotaku]]|date=July 7, 2014|accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> On the leaks, Vignocchi stated "Yeah, this year we definitely had a challenge with retail – putting out the sku plans and having those accessible by managers prior to announcements. But at the same time, as we've said internally – well, people care enough to talk about it, so we know we’re doing something special!"<ref name=News2>{{cite web|last1=Siegel|first1=Lucas|title=DISNEY INFINITY 2.0 Execs Talk Marvel, Disney, Tease STAR WARS for 2015|url=http://www.newsarama.com/21963-disney-infinity-2-0-execs-talk-marvel-disney-tease-star-wars-for-2015.html|website=newsarama.com|publisher=[[Newsarama]]|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>

==Reception==
{{Video game reviews
<!-- Aggregators -->
| MC = PS4: 71/100<ref name=MetacriticReview>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-4/disney-infinity-20-edition |title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Edition for PlayStation 4 Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><br />WIIU: 73/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/wii-u/disney-infinity-20-edition |title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Edition for Wii U Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><br />XONE: 73/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-one/disney-infinity-20-edition |title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Edition for Xbox One Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref><br />VITA: 74/100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/playstation-vita/disney-infinity-20-edition-marvel-super-heroes |title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Edition (Marvel Super Heroes) for PlayStation Vita Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=11 July 2018}}</ref>
<!-- Reviewers -->
| Destruct = 8/10<ref name=DestructoidReview>{{cite web|author=Chris Carter|title=Review: Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes|url=http://www.destructoid.com/review-disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-281121.phtml|website=destructoid.com|publisher=[[Destructoid]]|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref>
| GI = 6.5/10<ref name=GameInformerReview/>
| GameRev = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=GameRevolutionReview/>
| GSpot = 7/10<ref name=GameSpotReview/>
| GRadar = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=GamesRadarReview/>
| GT = 8/10<ref name=GameTrailersReview/>
| IGN = 6.8/10<ref name=IGNReview/>
| Joystiq = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=JoystiqReview>{{cite web|author=Xav de Matos|title=Disney Infinity 2.0 Marvel Super Heroes review: Super friends|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2014/09/19/disney-infinity-2-0-marvel-super-heroes-review-super-friends/|website=Joystiq.com|publisher=[[Joystiq]]|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref>
| rev1 = ''Hardcore Gamer''
| rev1Score = 4/5<ref name="hardcore gamer review" />
}}

Upon release, ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' received mixed to positive reviews from game critics. [[Review aggregator]] website [[Metacritic]] gave the PlayStation 4 version of the game 71/100.<ref name=MetacriticReview/>

While the new additions to game's Toybox mode received praise, ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''{{'}}s Playset mode was criticized. The Toybox was praised for its new additions by both David Roberts of [[GamesRadar]] and Randolph Ramsay of [[GameSpot]].<ref name=GameSpotReview>{{cite web|last1=Ramsay|first1=Randolph|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes -- 2.0 Edition Review|url=http://www.gamespot.com/reviews/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-2-0-edition-re/1900-6415877/|website=gamespot.com|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=GamesRadarReview>{{cite web|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes review|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/disney-infinity-20-review/|website=gamesradar.com|last1=Roberts|first1=David|publisher=[[GamesRadar]]|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> Roberts, however panned the game's "awkward combat, boring, repetitive quests and obtuse controls."<ref name=GamesRadarReview/> He also described the Avengers Playset as being too empty and bland.<ref name=GamesRadarReview/> Ramsay gave the game a more favorable review, but primarily found some of ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''{{'}}s technical hiccups and the need to unlock toys in the Toybox, which made some of his time playing the game adverse.<ref name=GameSpotReview/> Brandon Jones of [[GameTrailers]] praised the easier-to-use Toybox tools, but was disappointed by a lack of diversity from the game's Playsets.<ref name=GameTrailersReview>{{cite web|last1=Jones|first1=Brandon|title=Disney Infinity 2.0: Marvel Super Heroes - Review|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/reviews/caovu4/disney-infinity-2-0--marvel-super-heroes-review|website=gametrailers.com|publisher=[[GameTrailers]]|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, Daniel Krupa of [[IGN]] commended the game's improved combat, which made characters more interesting, and the more accessible Toybox mode.<ref name=IGNReview>{{cite web|last1=Krupa|first1=Daniel|title=DISNEY INFINITY 2.0: MARVEL SUPER HEROES REVIEW|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2014/09/19/disney-infinity-20-marvel-super-heroes-review|website=ign.com|publisher=[[IGN]]|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> He, like Roberts and Ramsay, criticized the game's lack of variety in its Playset mode, repetitive missions and "lifeless" version of New York City.<ref name=IGNReview/>

Andrew Reiner of [[Game Informer]] thought that ''The Avengers'', ''Guardians of the Galaxy'' and ''Spider-Man'' Playsets were "miserable adventures," the characters' controls were done well and that the character animations were well done.<ref name=GameInformerReview>{{cite web|last1=Reiner|first1=Andrew|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/disney_infinity_marvel_super_heroes/b/playstation4/archive/2014/09/18/artists-welcome-heroes-stay-away.aspx|website=gameinformer.com|publisher=[[Game Informer]]|accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref> Reiner, however, was not pleased with the music featured within all three of ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''{{'}}s Playsets, calling it "cringe-worthy."<ref name=GameInformerReview/> He also cited that the dubstep music featured in the ''Spider-Man'' Playset was poorly done.<ref name=GameInformerReview/> Blake Peterson of [[Game Revolution]] gave the game a more commendatory review, explaining that the game's improved combat, stronger level design (compared to the first game), expanded Toybox options, and the ability to personalize characters, were some of the major things that made the game worthwhile.<ref name=GameRevolutionReview>{{cite web|author=|title=Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes Review|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/review/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes|website=gamerevolution.com|publisher=[[Game Revolution]]|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> In spite of that, Peterson condemned ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes''{{'}}s bad driving mechanics, poor player training within Toybox mode and high cost to unlock content.<ref name=GameRevolutionReview/> Steve Hannley of Hardcore Gamer also gave the game a positive review, scoring it a 4/5, saying "Toy Box mode has been notably upgraded and overall gameplay is more polished, while increased depth will have players of all ages coming back for more,"  yet criticizing the "repetitive" Play Sets.<ref name="hardcore gamer review">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2014/09/19/review-disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes-2-0-edition/106122/|title=Review: Disney Infinity Marvel Super Heroes - 2.0 Edition |work=Hardcore Gamer|publisher=Hardcore Gamer|first=Steve|last=Hannley|date=19 September 2014|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref>

At the 2014 [[National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]] (NAVGTR) awards ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' was nominated for the ''Game, Franchise Family''.<ref>{{cite web|title=NAVGTR Awards (2014)|url=http://navgtr.org/archives/2445|website=National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers}}</ref> It was nominated in the [[2015 Kids' Choice Awards]] for "Most Addicting Game", but lost to ''[[Minecraft]]''.

===Sales===
Michael Pachter, of [[Wedbush Securities]] forecast that about 3.2 million copies of the game would be sold.<ref name=Forecast>{{cite web|last1=Gaudiosi|first1=John|title=Michael Pachter, video game analyst at Wedbush Securities forecasts steady sales of approximately 3.2 million Disney Infinity 2.0 video games, but he thinks the Marvel play sets and figures will double in sales thanks to the strong international appeal of super heroes.|url=http://fortune.com/2014/06/24/disney-infinity-marvel-super-heroes/|website=fortune.com|publisher=Fortune|accessdate=1 August 2014}}</ref> He also forecast that the Marvel Playsets and figurines would double in sales, due to strong international appeal of super heroes.<ref name=Forecast/> Prior to the game's release, Disney was initially surprised by the popularity of the [[Venom (Marvel Comics character)|Venom]] figurine. Disney has cited the character's design and abilities as its source of high sales.<ref name=Herald>{{cite web|last1=Graser|first1=Marc|title=Even Disney is surprised by the success of 'Disney Infinity'|url=http://bostonherald.com/entertainment/lifestyle/2014/07/even_disney_is_surprised_by_the_success_of_disney_infinity|website=bostonherald.com|publisher=Boston Herald|accessdate=26 July 2014}}</ref> [[Rocket Raccoon]] was the best selling character, since becoming available to pre-order in July 2014.<ref name=Yondu>{{cite web|last1=Graser|first1=Marc|title=‘Guardians of the Galaxy’ to Break Records for ‘Disney Infinity’ (EXCLUSIVE)|url=https://variety.com/2014/digital/games/guardians-of-the-galaxy-breaks-records-for-disney-infinity-exclusive-1201302907/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> The Rocket figurine sold almost twice as much as the Mike Wazowski and Elsa figurines from the first game.<ref name=Yondu/> Those two figurines were the best selling characters of ''Disney Infinity''.<ref name=Yondu/> The Rocket Raccoon figurine was later reported to have tripled in sales, but Disney declined to provide actual sales figures.<ref name=Yondu/> [[Groot]] was the third selling character, only behind Venom.<ref name=Yondu/>
Disney expects ''Disney Infinity'' and ''Disney Infinity: Marvel Super Heroes'' to generate $1 billion in sales.<ref>{{cite web|last1=C.|first1=Traci|title=Disney Expects Sales of Infinity Game to Reach $1 Billion after 2.0 Version Launches this Fall|url=http://www.wdwforgrownups.com/articles/disney-expects-sales-infinity-game-reach-1-billion-after-20-version-launches-fall|website=wdwforgrownups.com|publisher=Walt Disney World for Grown Ups|accessdate=3 August 2014}}</ref>

==Sequel==
{{main|Disney Infinity 3.0}}

A potential third installment in the ''Disney Infinity'' game franchise, and the inclusion of characters from [[Star Wars]] have been teased at by executive producer John Vignocchi.<ref name=SW2015/> When talking about the franchise's future, Vignocchi stated that "2015 is not so ''far, far away'' anymore, is it?"<ref name=SW2015>{{cite web|last1=McMillan|first1=Graeme|title=26 17 HRS Will 'Disney Infinity' Add 'Star Wars' in 2015?|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/will-disney-infinity-add-star-728299 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref>

On May 5, 2015, Disney announced a follow-up game through ''[[Game Informer]]'', ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]'', for release on [[Xbox 360]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[Wii U]], [[iOS]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[Xbox One]], and [[PlayStation 4]] in 2015, featuring characters from the ''[[Star Wars]]'' universe and other new Disney characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2015/05/05/june-cover-revealed-disney-infinity-3-0.aspx|title=June Cover Revealed – Disney Infinity 3.0|first=Jeff|last=Cork|date=May 5, 2015|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref>

